{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between earthing system arrangements and the specific functional roles of ADS components.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To ensure Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS) works, we must correctly identify the earthing system (TT, TN-S, or TN-C-S) and the specific conductors involved. Each conductor has a unique role: the Earthing Conductor links the installation to the source, the CPC protects individual circuits, and Bonding creates an equipotential zone.",
      "In a TN-C-S system, the supplier provides a terminal where the earth and neutral are separated after being combined in the street. The way we connect our installation to this terminal determines the safety and integrity of the entire ADS strategy."
    ],
    "questionText": "A technician is connecting a 16mm² green-and-yellow cable from the supplier's intake terminal (where the earth and neutral have just been separated) to the installation's Main Earthing Terminal (MET). Explain why this specific cable is technically defined as the 'Earthing Conductor' rather than a 'CPC' or 'Main Protective Bonding' in this TN-C-S setup.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The cable is the Earthing Conductor because it is the primary link between the MET and the means of earthing (the supplier's terminal).",
      "It is not a CPC because it does not protect an individual circuit.",
      "It is not Main Protective Bonding because its purpose is to provide the main fault return path to the source, not to create an equipotential zone by connecting to extraneous metalwork like gas or water pipes.",
      "In a TN-C-S system, this conductor specifically bridges the gap between the consumer's MET and the supplier's combined-then-separated earth/neutral point."
    ],
    "hint": "Focus on the 'master' role of this cable. Does it serve one circuit, the whole house's connection to the grid, or is it just equalising voltage on a pipe?"
  }
